According to the quick start repo making the actual Browser Window object null on the close event should be all you need to do.

``` javascript
win.on('closed', function() {
  win = null;
});
```

If that is in your main process then `win.destroy();` will fire off the close event and destroy it without interruption. Otherwise you will need to use `win.close();` to simulate the user clicking the close button.

